{
    "text": "Wordle brain function",
    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:29:08 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "Just guessing here about our brains.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:29:15 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a132915"
        },
        {
            "text": "Letter frequencies in English are known. Letter pair frequencies are known. Cryptographers use them. Computers can use them in solving puzzles. My guess is that Wordle players are informally, unsystematically, inexactly using their knowledge of these frequencies as they play.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:30:22 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133022"
        },
        {
            "text": "A computer could be programed to offer a Wordle player a dashboard that shows the following, step-by-step as you play, but I think our acquaintance with English word patterns provide something kind of like it, in an impressionistic fashion, as we play.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:30:17 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133017",
            "subs": [
                {
                    "text": "Most common as-yet-unguessed vowels",
                    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:32:18 GMT",
                    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133218"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Most common as-yet-unguessed consonants",
                    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:32:44 GMT",
                    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133244"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Most common as-yet-unguessed vowel pairs (like the ee in street)",
                    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:32:55 GMT",
                    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133255"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Most common as-yet-unguessed consonant pairs",
                    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:33:05 GMT",
                    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133305"
                },
                {
                    "text": "Most common first letters in a word, last letters in a word, etc.",
                    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:36:02 GMT",
                    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133602"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "It would be interesting to know how much an experienced player's guesses, based on an impressionistic sense of letter frequency (if I'm right about that), resemble or not what the data about letter frequency shows.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:36:56 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a133656"
        },
        {
            "text": "PS. I can't tell if the analysis done by <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2022/upshot/wordle-bot.html\">WordleBot</a> is a close match for this line of thinking or not. In any case, it is provided after the fact, not as a dashboard in play.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:56:04 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/132908.html?title=wordleBrainFunction#a135604"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "text": "Pioneering social behavior",
    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:56:43 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://scripting.com/2022/09/17/135643.html?title=pioneeringSocialBehavior",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "The frontier in new models for social networks are systems that work wonderfully with small numbers of users. The size of a PTA or bowling team. And to limit forms of expression so that it can't devolve.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:56:47 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://scripting.com/2022/09/17/135643.html?title=pioneeringSocialBehavior#a135647"
        },
        {
            "text": "For the last 50 years we've been building social networks that grow without limit, and give the users power to say anything. We keep repeating this, and being shocked when they devolve to the most crude form of human behavior.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:57:10 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://scripting.com/2022/09/17/135643.html?title=pioneeringSocialBehavior#a135710"
        },
        {
            "text": "Instead let's pioneer of new forms of social behavior.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:57:16 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://scripting.com/2022/09/17/135643.html?title=pioneeringSocialBehavior#a135716"
        },
        {
            "text": "Hopefully something better than devolution, more useful at solving the problems we have.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 13:59:15 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://scripting.com/2022/09/17/135643.html?title=pioneeringSocialBehavior#a135915"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "text": "Doggy life",
    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:12:47 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "A friend, Stephen, said that as far as he could tell going on a walk was easily the best part of a dog's day. Maybe related, Billy Collins has a poem (or two) in which a dog does the speaking. The <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DOvbl3ZPPV4\">dog complains</a> about how utterly boring it is to smell the same inside-the-house, already-pawed-by-the-owner smells hour after hour, day after day.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:12:54 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife#a141254"
        },
        {
            "text": "Out the window just now, across the street in the grassy part of the ball field: a guy, his medium-sized dog, and a frisbee ring. Over on the street, two women joggers trotted by and the guy stopped looking at his dog for a moment. Then he turned his gaze back to his dog. The dog rolled over and started twisting and rubbing its back in the grass. No doubt breaking the leaves, stirring up a bit of fresh dirt, maybe crushing a few bugs. This turning and rubbing went on and on.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:14:33 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife#a141433"
        },
        {
            "text": "I'm no expert, but that dog seemed very, very happy. All the guy was doing was observe him. At the end, popping up on, refreshed and vigorous and alive.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:17:51 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife#a141751"
        },
        {
            "text": "My guess is that a back rub felt great, the length of which was chosen by the increasingly happy creature, and that this back rub took place in an invisible cloud of fascinating and utterly vivid fresh scents. Not pale, distant on-the-wind scents either. Right up there in the passages of your nose nearby scents. Just minted scents.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:18:37 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife#a141837"
        },
        {
            "text": "Chosen freely by the dog, lasting as long as the dog wanted, a massage in an aroma cloud of fresh earth with its botanicals and biologicals. Doggy life is good, I'm guessing the dog thought there by the end.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:20:36 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife#a142036"
        },
        {
            "text": "But just guessing. I don't really know that much about dogs.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 14:22:30 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/141247.html?title=doggyLife#a142230"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "text": "How to think about a new tool",
    "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 16:52:35 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/165235.html?title=howToThinkAboutANewTool",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "Many ways to think about a new tool. What it looks like, where it came from, how its parts move. For a user, how it extends the perceiving power of the senses, the manipulative powers of the hands, the neural pathways active in the brain, the reach of public speech. How it enables not fully predictable practices through which a new community might imagine itself step by stumble by step into hopeful or bitter existence.",
            "created": "Sat, 17 Sep 2022 16:52:41 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/17/165235.html?title=howToThinkAboutANewTool#a165241"
        }
    ]
}

